f narrow HI channels is often attributed to velocity caustics. We\nconjecture instead that the small-scale structure and narrow linewidths typical\nof CNM explain the observed relationship between the SPS and channel width.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Feb 2019 19:00:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 28 Feb 2019 19:38:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 10 Apr 2019 03:29:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-11"}
{"id":"1902.01410","submitter":"Yuta Hamada","authors":"Yuta Hamada, Arthur Hebecker, Gary Shiu, Pablo Soler","title":"Understanding KKLT from a 10d perspective","comments":"23 pages; v2: Refs. and more details on the chosen technical approach\n  added; v3: published in JHEP","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/JHEP06(2019)019","report-no":"CCTP-2019-2, ITCP-IPP 2019/2, MAD-TH-19-02","categories":"hep-th astro-ph.CO hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Some of the most well-celebrated constructions of metastable de Sitter vacua\nfrom string theory, such as the KKLT proposal, involve the interplay of gaugino\ncondensation on a D7-brane stack and an uplift by a positive tension object.\nThese constructions have recently been challenged using arguments that rely on\nthe trace-reversed and integrated 10d Einstein equation. We give a critical\nassessment of such concerns. We first relate an integrated 10d Einstein\nequation to the extremization condition for a 10d-derived 4d effective\npotential. Then we argue how to obtain the latter from a 10d action which\nincorporates gaugino condensation in a (recently proposed) manifestly finite,\nperfect-square form. This effective potential is consistent with 4d\nsupergravity and does not present obstacles for an uplifted minimum. Moreover,\nwithin standard approximations, we understand the uplift explicitly in one of\nthe popular versions of the integrated 10d equation. Our conclusion is that de\nSitter constructions of the KKLT type cannot be dismissed simply based on the\nintegrated 10d equations considered so far.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Feb 2019 19:00:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 6 Mar 2019 03:04:45 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 11 Jun 2019 05:48:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-06-12"}
